  "chunk_index": 11,
  "summary": "Inspector Corradino conducts several interviews regarding the robbery at Miss Blacklock's estate. He first speaks with an elderly gardener, who mentions local rumors and labor shortages. The gardener notes that Ned Barker blames movies for the crime, while Tom Liley suspects the cook, a foreigner, is responsible. At a pub, a woman named Maryann suggests Miss Blacklock possesses valuables, though a woman named Flore claims the lady's pearls are merely costume jewelry. Jim Hawkins adds that his wife believes Micky was involved due to her temper.\n\nCorradino then finds Phyllis Hammond in the apple orchard. She explains that she finished her work around 5:30 PM, watered the greenhouse, and entered the house through the side door, which she always locks. Regarding the robbery, she describes being by the fireplace when the lights went out and a man with a revolver and a flashlight entered. She initially thought it was a joke until a gun fired. She notes that the flashlight illuminated a pale Miss Bonner and that Micky began screaming. Following the shot, Edmund Swetnam and Patrick Simmons used lighters to navigate to the hallway, where Swetnam slapped Midge to silence her. Phyllis states she does not know the deceased man and has never seen him at the manor. She denies having significant valuables beyond an engagement ring and some brooches.\n\nFinally, Corradino encounters Mrs. Lucas in the garden. She expresses disapproval of strangers in the garden and suggests that the police have become lax due to the rise in robberies.",
